Accept-reject methods

  • There are many distributions where
    • transform methods or
    • inverse CDF technique fails
  • For these cases, we need indirect methods
    • We generate a candidate random variable
    • Only accept it subject to passing a test
  • This class of methods is extremely powerful.
    • It will allow us to simulate from virtually any distribution.

The Fundamental Theorem of Simulation:

Simulating \(X \sim f(x)\) is equivalent to simulating \((X,U)\sim Unif((x,u):0 < u < f(x))\).

AcceptReject Methods

  • Only require the functional form of the density \(f\) of interest
  • Choose \(g\) such that it is simpler to simulate random variables from \(g\)

  • Terminology: \(f\) = target density, \(g\) =candidate or instrumental density

  • The only constraints we impose on this candidate density \(g\)
    • \(f\) and \(g\) have compatible supports (i.e., \(g(x) > 0\) when \(f(x) > 0\) ).
    • There is a constant \(M\) with \(\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \leq M\) for all \(x\)
    • Ideally, the function \(g(x)\) is close to \(f(x)\), ie \(M\) is as close to 1 as possible

Accept-reject algorithm

\(X \sim f\) can be simulated as follows.

  1. Generate \(Y \sim g\) and, independently, generate \(U \sim U[0,1]\)
  2. If \(U \leq \frac{f(Y)}{M g(Y)}\), set \(X=Y\) > Accept Y
  3. If the inequality is not satised, we then discard \(Y\) and \(U\) and start again > Reject Y

Note that

  • \(M = sup_x \frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\)
  • \(Prob(Accept) = \frac{1}{M}\), Expected waiting time for accept is \(M\).

In short - Accept-Reject Algorithm

  1. Generate \(Y \sim g, U \sim U[0,1]\)
  2. Accept \(~X = Y~\) if \(~U \leq \frac{f(Y)}{M g(Y)}\)
  3. Return to 1 otherwise.

Algorithm and R Code

  1. Generate \(Y \sim g, U \sim U[0,1]\)
  2. Accept \(~X = Y~\) if \(~U \leq \frac{f(Y)}{M g(Y)}\)
  3. Return to 1 otherwise.

R code for a single generation \(y\) from \(f\) would look like:

  • Write a function randg that generates from \(g\) or use a built-in one
u=runif(1)*M
y=randg(1)
while ( u>f(y)/g(y) ) # reject, generate new u, y.
  {
  u=runif(1)*M 
  y=randg(1) 
  }

Several things to note

  • Since \(f\) and \(g\) represent rvs, so does the ratio \(\frac{f(Y)}{M g(Y)}\)
  • The above ratio is independent of the \(U\) generated in Step 1.
  • Since \(sup_x \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \leq M\) we have \(0 < \frac{f(Y)}{M g(Y)} < 1\)
  • The number of times \(N\) that steps 1 and 2 need to be called (i.e, the number of iterations needed to successfully generate X) is itself a rv and has a geometric distribution with success probability \[p= \displaystyle P(U \leq \frac{f(Y)}{M g(Y)})\]
  • So, \(P(N=n)= (1-p)^{n-1}p\), \(n \geq 1\) and \(E[N]= \frac{1}{p}\)
  • Thus on average the number of iterations required is given by \(E[N] = \frac{1}{p}\)

  • \(p = P(Accept) = \frac{1}{M}\) since
    • \(p = \displaystyle P(U \leq \frac{f(Y)}{M g(Y)})\)
    • Conditioning on \(Y=y\), \(P(U \leq \frac{f(Y)}{M g(Y)}~| Y=y) = \frac{f(y)}{M g(y)}\)
    • Unconditioning and Since \(Y\) has density \(g(y)\), integrating wrt \(y\) \[ p = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{f(y)}{M g(y)} g(y) dy = \frac{1}{M}\]
  • \(E(N) = M\), the bounding constant.
  • For fastest termination of algorithm(least number of iterations to generate from \(X\sim f\)), choose smallest possible \(M= sup_x \frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\).

AcceptReject Algorithm Example 1:

Normals from Double Exponentials:

  • Target density: \(~X \sim f(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{\frac{-x^{2}}{2}}\)
  • Candidate/instrumental density \(~Y \sim g(y) = \frac{1}{2}e^{-|y|}\)

\[ \frac{f(y)}{g(y)} = \frac{\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{\frac{-y^{2}}{2}}}{\frac{1}{2}e^{-|y|}} \leq \frac{2}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^\frac{1}{2} \approx 1.3154 \] - \(\frac{f(y)}{g(y)}\) has maximum at \(y=1\)

  • Accept \(Y\) if \(U \frac{\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{\frac{-y^{2}}{2}}}{\frac{2}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{2}e^{-|y|}} = e^{(.5Y^2 +|Y|.5)}\)

Theory: Accept-Reject Algorithm

  • Why does this method work?
  • Target is \(X, f\) and instrumental is \(Y,g\),the conditional pdf of \(Y\) when accepted \[P(Y = x | Accept ) = P(Y =x ~ |~ U \leq \frac{f(Y )}{Mg(Y )}) = P(X = x) = f(x)\]
    • Using definition of conditional probability and \(p = P(U \leq \frac{f(Y )}{Mg(Y )})=\frac{1}{M}\)

\[P(Y = x~ |~ U \leq \frac{f(Y )}{Mg(Y )}) = \frac{P(Y = x~ ,~ U \leq \frac{f(Y )}{Mg(Y )})}{P(U \leq \frac{f(Y )}{Mg(Y )})} =M. P(Y = x~ , ~ U \leq \frac{f(Y )}{Mg(Y )})\] \[ = M P(Y = x) P( U \leq \frac{f(x )}{Mg(x )})= Mg(x)P(U \leq \frac{f(x )}{Mg(x )}) = Mg(x)\frac{f(x )}{Mg(x )}=f(x) \]

  • Simulating from \(g\), the output of this algorithm is exactly distributed from \(f\)

Further notes about AR algorithm

  • The AcceptReject method is applicable in any dimension

  • As long as \(g\) is a density over the same space as \(f\)

  • \[ P(accept | Y ) = P( U\leq \frac{f(Y)}{Mg(Y)} | Y ) = f(Y)/Mg(Y) \]

  • \[ P(accept) = \sum_y P(accept | y )g(y) = 1/M\]

  • Only need to know \(f/g\) up to a constant, dont need constants in the density
  • Only need an upper bound on \(M\)
  • Ignoring normalizing constants in density gives an upper bound \(M_1\) on \(M= sup_x \frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\) calculated with density.
  • So, if constants are ignored and you get an upper bound \(M_1\), \(P(acceptance)\) is no longer \(\frac{1}{M_1}\)
  • Rule of Thumb: \(g\) should have thicker tails than \(f\)

  • Pay attention to acceptance rate when you dont use constants in accept-reject decision criterion.

AcceptReject Algorithm Example 2:

Beta from Uniform:

  • To Generate \(X \sim beta(3,3)\).
  • Use a uniform candidate
    • Has heavier tails than Beta(3,3). Is this a good candidate?

Plot it

Theory:

  • Target density has PDF \[ f(x)\propto x^{2}(1-x)^{2}. \]
  • Candidate \(g(x)=1\) (uniform)

  • Compute \(M\) \[max_{0 < x < 1}x^{2}(1-x)^{2}=0.5^{4}=0.0625\]

  • Accept \(Y\) if \(U \leq \frac{x^{2}(1-x)^{2}}{0.0625}\)

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
nsim=10000
Y=runif(nsim)
hist(Y,freq=F,col="gray",breaks=50)
for(i in 1:nsim) Y[i]=Y[i]*(runif(1)<(Y[i]^2*(1-Y[i])^2/.0625))
Y<-Y[Y!=0]                  #eliminate zeros
length(Y)/nsim              #percent accepted
1/0.0625 # not 1/M
hist(Y,freq=F,col="red",breaks=50)

Simulating Normals from Cauchy

What do the pdfs look like?

Simulating Normals from Cauchy

Why do this?

- Cauchy has heavier tails than normal - makes a good instrumental density
- simulate cauchy by inverse CDF - easy

Simulating Normals using Cauchy random variables.

Here our target density is the standard Normal distribution with PDF

\[f(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} e^{-x^{2}/2}\]

Candidate/Instrumental density: Cauchy(0,1) random variable has PDF

\[g(x)=\frac{1}{\pi}\,\frac{1}{1+x^{2}},\quad -\infty < x < \infty\]

  • Cauchy CDF \[F(x) =\mathbb{P}(X\leq x) =\int_{-\infty}^{x}\frac{1}{\pi}\,\frac{1}{1+t^{2}} dt\] \[ =\left.\frac{1}{\pi}\tan^{-1}(t)\right|_{t=-\infty}^{x}=\frac{1}{\pi}\left(\tan^{-1}x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right).\]
  • It is now easy to calculate the inverse transformation to simulate: \[\pi y =\tan^{-1}x+\pi/2\] \[\pi(y-1/2) =\tan^{-1}x\] \[\tan(\pi(y-1/2)) =x=F^{-1}(y)\]

and its inverse CDF is

\[ F^{-1}(y) = x = \tan(\pi(y-1/2)) \] So it is EASY to simulate from a Cauchy via inverse CDF.

Simulating Normals using Cauchy random variables.

Cauchy has heavier tails than normal - makes a good instrumental density.

Finding the M such that Normal < M. Cauchy \[\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} e^{-x^{2}/2} \leq M\,\frac{1}{\pi(1+x^{2})},\quad\mbox{or}\] \(\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{2}}(1+x^{2}) e^{-x^{2}/2} \leq M\)

  • Numerically, maximum of the LHS occurs when \(x=1\), and that maximum value is \(M \approx 1.5203469\).
  • On the average we need to generate approximately 1.52 Cauchys before we will get a Normal.
  • Probability of acceptance approximately 1/M=0.6548.(we used densities!)

Simulating Normals using Cauchy random variables.

Algorithm:

  • Generate \(U \sim Unif(0,1)\) and \(Y \sim Cauchy(0,1)\);
  • Accept \(X = Y\) if \(U < f(Y)/Mg(Y)\);
  • Return to 1. otherwise.

Theoritical probability of acceptance approximately 0.6548

and via actual simulation

## [1] 0.6594131

Code

#Simulating Normal with a Cauchy
#We cover the standard Normal density with a Cauchy proposal density
# and use the accept-reject algorithm. 
# randnorm function 
# randnorm.R

randnorm <- function(n){
  M <- 1.5203 # bound used in A/R algo
  i <- 0; N <- 0 # init and storage
  z <- rep(0, times = n)
  while(i < n){ # keep going until n accepts
      x <- tan(pi*(runif(1) - 0.5))  # simulate a Cauchy
      u <- runif(1)                  # simulate a Uniform
      f <- 1/sqrt(2*pi)*exp(-x^2/2)  # compute f(x)
      g <- 1/pi/(1+x^2)  # compute g(x)
      
      if (u <= f/M/g){ # got another accept
        i <- i + 1
        z[i] <- x # save this one
      }
      
      N <- N + 1 # keep track of num trials
    }
list(z = z, accept = n/N) # variates and percent accepted
}
     

tmp <- randnorm(10000)
tmp$accept

Simulating from Discrete distributions.

We want to simulate from a discrete RV \(X\) that takes values \(1,2,...,10\) with probabilities

\[p = (.11, .12, .09, .08, .12, .10, .09, .09, .10, .10)\]

These are the target \(p_{j}\)s.

Choose candidate density Y: \(Y\sim DiscUnif(1,2,\ldots,10)\) with \(q_{j}=0.1\), \(j=1,\ldots,10\).

Next, we need to find

\[M=\max_{j}\frac{p_{j}}{q_{j}}=\frac{0.12}{0.10}=1.2.\]

AR Algorithm:

  1. Generate \(Y \sim DiscUnif(1,10)\) and \(U\sim Unif(0,1)\);
  2. Accept \(X = Y\) if \(U < p_{Y}/1.2 q_{Y}\);
  3. Return to 1 otherwise.

Exercise

Generating one observation from the above discrete uniform

mydiscrete1 <- function(){
  accept <- FALSE
  p <- c(.11, .12, .09, .08, .12, .10, .09, .09, .10, .10)
  while (!accept){
    y <- sample(10, size = 1);
    u <- runif(1)
    accept <- (u < p[y]/(1.2*0.1));
  }
  return(y)
}

y <- mydiscrete1()

Simulate a whole vector of discrete RVs, all IID with density p

Generalize our function to include arguments \(\mathbf{p}\) and \(n\), the desired length of simulation.

#This function generates a discrete distribution via the accept-reject algorithm.
mydiscreteN <- function(p,N){
  # p is the desired target density on 1,...,k.
  # N is the number of observations desired
  x <- rep(0, times = N)# initialize
  k <- length(p)        # the support of p
  M <- k*max(p)   # the bound size
  for(i in seq.int(N)){
    accept <- FALSE   # initialize
    while (!accept){  # continue until we accept
      y <- sample(k, size = 1)  # y is disc unif 1...k
      u <- runif(1)         # u is unif(0,1)
      accept <- ( u < p[y]/(M*1/k) )# is TRUE if A/R condition satisfied
    }
    x[i] <- y # this y is a good one
  }
  return(x)
}

p <- c(.11, .12, .09, .08, .12, .10, .09, .09, .10, .10)
x <- mydiscreteN(p, 10000)
y<-table(x) #a contingency table of the counts at each combination of factor levels.
z<-prop.table(x)
plot(prop.table(table(x)), ylab = "Relative frequency")

AcceptReject Algorithm Lab

Simulating Beta(2.5, 4.5) Random Variables: Which method is better?

  • Earlier, AR with uniform candidate or via transform of Gamma rv, we could simulate Beta(a,b) only for iteger parameters.
  • AR can simulate all Beta distributions, even non-integral

We wish to simulate Beta(2.5,4.5) random variables with target density \[ f(x) \propto x^{1.5}(1-x)^{3.5}. \]

To do this we will use the Accept/Reject Algorithm with two different instrumental densities.

  • Method I: Use uniform RVs with instrumental density \[ g_{1}(x) = 1,\quad 0 < x < 1. \]
  • you may use \(M \approx 0.0472\).
  • to simulate from \(g_{1}\) use the command x <- runif(1).
  • Method II: Use the average of two uniform RVs with instrumental density \[ g_{2}(x) = 2 - |4x - 2|,\quad 0 < x <1. \] -Notes:
  • you may use \(M \approx 0.0554\).
  • the R function for absolute value is abs.
  • to simulate from \(g_{2}\) use the command x <- mean(runif(2)).

Question: Which method is better?

  • Write a program that simulates 10,000 Beta(2.5,4.5) random variables using both methods.
  • Compare the acceptance rates and decide which one is the better algorithm.
  • Graph histograms of your results.
